  <!-- ====== PRODUCTION CONSIDERATIONS ====== -->
  <section class="content-layer section-divider px-4 py-16 sm:px-6 lg:px-8" style="background: #16131180;">
    <div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl space-y-8 text-left">
      <h2>Production considerations</h2>

      <div class="mt-4 space-y-6">
        <div>
          <h3>Project isolation</h3>
          <p class="mt-2" style="color: var(--text-muted);">Multi-tenant memory requires per-project data isolation. Row-Level Security (RLS) with FORCE policies ensures each project's observations are visible only to authorized agents. Without RLS, a fallback to a generic project namespace can leak observations across projects — a real incident we documented and fixed permanently (LEAK-01 postmortem).</p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h3>Observation intelligence</h3>
          <p class="mt-2" style="color: var(--text-muted);">Raw observations accumulate fast. Without enrichment — deduplication, supersession, decay — your memory graph becomes noise. The Morpheus pipeline processes observations automatically: normalizing format, deduplicating redundant entries, superseding stale information with newer versions, and generating compressed session summaries. This keeps the signal-to-noise ratio high as your project scales.</p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h3>Token budget management</h3>
          <p class="mt-2" style="color: var(--text-muted);">Every token injected into context costs money. Progressive context injection with a ~7,000-token budget (vs. 25,000+ for full context) reduces costs by ~90% with comparable accuracy (arXiv:2504.19413, ECAI 2025). Managing this budget — choosing which observations to include and which to exclude — is the core engineering challenge of production memory systems.</p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h3>Bring Your Own Key (BYOK)</h3>
          <p class="mt-2" style="color: var(--text-muted);">The Morpheus pipeline and embedding generation require LLM and embedding API calls. BYOK lets you provide your own provider keys — OpenAI, Anthropic, or any compatible endpoint. Your AI keys are encrypted at rest and never shared. BYOK on every tier means no feature gating for core functionality.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ====== CODE EXAMPLE ====== -->
  <section class="content-layer section-divider px-4 py-16 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
    <div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl space-y-8 text-left">
      <h2>Getting started with AI agent memory</h2>
      <p style="color: var(--text-muted);">Three steps to give your agent persistent, project-scoped memory:</p>

      <div class="code-terminal mt-6">
        <div class="code-terminal-bar">
          <span class="code-terminal-dot code-terminal-dot-red"></span>
          <span class="code-terminal-dot code-terminal-dot-yellow"></span>
          <span class="code-terminal-dot code-terminal-dot-green"></span>
          <span class="ml-4 font-mono text-[10px]" style="color: var(--text-muted);">quickstart.sh</span>
        </div>
        <div class="code-terminal-body">
          <pre><span class="syn-cmt"># 1. Add MCP server to your agent config</span>
&#123;
  "mcpServers": &#123;
    "telepathine": &#123;
      "command": "npx",
      "args": ["-y", "@ai-memory/mcp-server"],
      "env": &#123;
        "TELEPATHINE_API_KEY": "your_api_key_here"
      &#125;
    &#125;
  &#125;
&#125;

<span class="syn-cmt"># 2. Start a session — your agent records observations</span>
$ curl -X POST https://api.telepathine.ai/v1/sessions \
  -H "Authorization: Bearer $TELEPATHINE_API_KEY" \
  -d '&#123;"project":"my-app"&#125;'

<span class="syn-cmt"># 3. New session — prior context surfaces automatically</span>
$ curl https://api.telepathine.ai/v1/context/inject?projects=my-app \
  -H "Authorization: Bearer $TELEPATHINE_API_KEY"
<span class="syn-cmt"># → ~7,000 tokens of relevant context</span>
<span class="syn-cmt"># → 90% token cost reduction vs. full history</span></pre>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
